or">Linus Torvalds &lt;&gt;</td></tr><tr><td class="lp">Subject</td><td class="rp" itemprop="name">Re: 2.2.0 and egcs 1.1 was Re: Sorry, wrong gcc-version</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody"><br /><br />On Mon, 26 Oct 1998, Khimenko Victor wrote:<br />&gt; LT&gt; The assembler used to be correct, and the gcc people unilaterally decided<br />&gt; LT&gt; to change the rules.<br />&gt; <br />&gt; It's their right to change rules. And now this assembler is incompatible with<br />&gt; egcs 1.1b (it's not "incorrect" since there are no standards for such assembler).<br />&gt; And thus should be fixed.<br /><br />It's their right to change the rules, yes.<br /><br />It's not their right to then suddenly say that everybody who plays with<br />the old rules is "broken". As a result, I still consider the older gcc's<br />to be the default compiler. <br /><br />The thing is, that the Linux kernel is one of the very very few pieces of<br />code that really exercises some of the gcc features. That's sad, because<br />it means that when the gcc people see a bug-report about Linux, they<br />apparently think that "hey, we're seeing so many Linux kernel bug-reports<br />and so few of anything else that it must be a kernel problem rather than a<br />compiler problem". Instead of realizing that the reason there are problems<br />with Linux that do not crop up anywhere else is that a kernel is special,<br />and has things that no other program tends to have. <br /><br />As a result, neither party is really willing to talk to the other party. <br />Yes, I'm guilty of that too, but I just got fed up with some of the<br />responses to my complaints about real gcc bugs. <br /><br />It's entirely possible that egcs-1.1b (or whatever the current egcs is) is<br />bug-free. But I'm not even testing it because of my bad experiences with<br />some of the previous bugs. <br /><br />And I also acknowledge that gcc-2.7.2 often may have the same bugs, and<br />that they just aren't instantiated due to not doing some of the new kinds<br />of optimizations. But I have heard egcs people mention this as some kind<br />of excuse to move up to a new compiler that has the same bugs and _shows_<br />them, and I don't follow that logic at all.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br />-<br />To unsubscribe from this list: send the line "unsubscribe linux-kernel" in<br />the body of a message to majordomo&#64;vger.rutgers.edu<br />Please read the FAQ at <a href="http://www.tux.org/lkml/">http://www.tux.org/lkml/</a><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
